	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1459_01.jpg"/> The persons in question have given us the following information: Our father was a grain
				dealer. He had a house and we made a decent living from our income until around <date when="1943">1943</date>, when the front was
				approaching our town. One year before the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">German
					occupation</term>, <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">soldiers</term> marching to the frontline came to
				the so-called Jewish street. They blocked a section of it and then entered each house. They were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">looting</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beating up</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> and sometimes even <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. Afterwards they chased the people out
				of the houses and forced them to do <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-555" type="subject">punitive
					exercises</term> on the street. Later it turned even worse, since they started firing and as far as I remember, they even mounted
				a cannon in the street. A few people <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">died</term> or
				were wounded in that incident. After the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">German
					occupation</term> those kinds of acts became common occurrences and were institutionalised. The <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655"
					type="subject">looting</term> and searching for money and jewellery all the time. We were very scared. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1112" type="subject">mayor</term> was <persName ref="#ehri_et_engelbreckl"
					>Engelbreckl</persName> and we had no cause for complaint against him. However, the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarmes</term> saw to it that all the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-337" type="subject">anti-Jewish decrees</term> were put into effect
				ruthlessly. One day it was announced that all the Jews in town should <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-614" type="subject">move</term> into streets designated for them by 6
				o’clock the following day. We were allowed to take as many things as we could carry. However, two days later we had to move from the
				designated streets, since the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> had been
				restricted to an even smaller area. Therefore we had to move into another street, but that time we were given only half an hour to
				move and we were supervised by the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName>. Of course,
				they never forgot to beat us. All the Jews from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/700646/mukacheve.html">Munkács</placeName>
				remember the so-called <q>Black Sabbath</q>. The <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826"
					>men</term> were going to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term>
				that morning, but the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>
				<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-598">arrested</term> them on the way and said they would
				take them to work. Indeed, they took away ca. 200 <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826"
					>men</term> and made them remove the gates from the street-front and later rounded them up in the yard of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat them up</term> severely. <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1459_02.jpg"/> One of our uncles, <persName ref="#ehri_et_bleier_mendel">Mendel Bleier</persName>, was among
				them. The <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat him up</term> so badly that he was lying <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">ill</term> for a couple of days. After that, they
				forced the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826">men</term> to bring out all the
				furnishings from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term>. They even
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-350" type="subject">threw out</term> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-756" type="subject">Torah scrolls</term> and had the Jews wash the floor
				with their talliths. As far as I remember, some of the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826">men</term> who had been beaten to a bloody pulp <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">died</term> of their injuries. We had nothing to
				complain about with regard to the activity of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-873" type="subject"
					>Jewish Council</term>, including <persName ref="#ehri_et_segelstein">Segelstein</persName> and others. We had a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-855" type="subject">soup kitchen</term>, which provided the other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> in the brickyard with <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">food</term> as well. The <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545">ghetto</term> was surrounded by a fence and it was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-546" type="subject">not allowed to move</term> from one <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545">ghetto</term> to the other; only a half hour was given
				a day to do that. The <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545">ghetto</term> was guarded by
				military <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125" type="subject">gendarmes</term>, who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">collected</term> jewellery, money and all the
				valuables they could find. The internal order was maintained by the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_jewish_police">Jewish
					police</term>. We were staying in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject"
					>ghetto</term> for four weeks. One morning at 7 the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125">gendarmes</term> broke the gates in with rifle butts, entered the
				flats and chased all of us out. They were virtually dragging people out of bed. Meanwhile they were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beating</term> everybody mercilessly, including the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">children</term>. That was our most terrifying
				experience during our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deportation</term>. The <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1125">gendarmes</term> went from house to house joined by
				the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term>, who were also beating us. They jointly rounded up
				everybody on the marketplace, lined us up in rows of five and we were set off for the brickyard. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">cruelties</term> continued: those who could not keep
				pace were beaten to a pulp. Among many others, one of our relatives also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> during that trip, because he had a <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292">stroke</term> due to over-excitement. We stayed five
				more days in the brickyard <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term>. The <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> made the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826">men</term> do <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-555" type="subject">punitive exercises</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat them up</term> once again. Then they locked up
				religious <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826">men</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-555" type="subject">forced them to sign</term> a statement that read that
				they had taken the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-344">blood of a Christian girl</term>
				for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-756" type="subject">Passover</term> matzo. They beat the poor
				victims until they signed the statement. They took away the wealthy people and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term> them to a pulp as well. We had already
				packed up our luggage and we were ready to go when they searched us once again. If they found money or any valuable item on someone,
				they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term> that person to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term>. We remember an ethnic <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">German</term> named <persName ref="#ehri_et_sefcsik">Sefcsik</persName>, who
				was especially cruel. Before our departure they rounded up the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825"
					type="subject">girls</term> and had them disassemble the empty barracks of the <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545">ghetto</term>. Those who refused to go were beaten up. We heard that
				we would be taken to work in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/721378/diosgyor.html">Diósgyőr</placeName>. Soon they entrained
				us. Seventy people were put into our <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">cattle
					car</term>, which was an ambulance car with 15 people confined to a bed. Therefore it was very crowded. The passengers included a
				one-day-old <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">baby</term>, a little <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">boy</term> in plaster to the waist and an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-320" type="subject">insane</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">woman</term> as well as many patients from the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term> and people from the home for the aged.
				It is easy to imagine how terrible <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">journey</term> we
				had. Surprisingly enough, nobody <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">died</term> in our
				car. At departure we were given buckets for water as well as for the purpose of a WC. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-873" type="subject">Jewish Council</term> had <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> put into the cars as well. There was
				another search for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">valuables</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName>. The <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans"
					>Germans</term> took over the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> there
				and then we went further at the speed of a fast <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject"
					>train</term>. We arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2" type="camp"
					>Auschwitz</placeName> on <date when="1944-05-25">May 25</date> in the early morning. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">Polish prisoners</term> in striped <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term> assisted in detraining us. We had to
				leave behind our luggage. They lined up the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826"
					>men</term> and the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">women</term> separately.
				Then they divided the <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">women</term> into two groups:
				some of us were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">sent</term> to the right and the
				others to the left. After that, we went to the bath where our heads were shaven and we got rags in return for our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothes</term>. Our better <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">shoes</term> were taken away as well. <pb n="3"
					facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1459_03.jpg"/> We were housed in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496"
					type="subject">camp</term> C. One thousand of us <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-486" type="subject"
					>stayed</term> in one block and 12 of us on one bunk. The wake-up call was at 3 in the morning and then we had to line up for
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term>, which sometimes lasted as long
				as three or four hours. We were not allowed to leave the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487"
					type="subject">roll call</term> area until the numbers did not match. Afterwards we went to the block totally exhausted and we got
				some plain <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">coffee</term>. We got half a litre of
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">soup</term> at noon in large pots. Spoons and
				plates were unknown there and therefore 12 of us had to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">drink</term> from the same pot one after the other. We got <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term> only in the afternoon. Then we had to
				line up for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term> at least for two hours
				and the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Zulage</term> was distributed only after
				that. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">Selections</term> began about two or three
				weeks later. I, the aforementioned <persName ref="#ehri_et_bleier_berta">Berta Bleier</persName>, was sent to <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> in the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_camp_kitchens"
					>kitchen</term> in <date when="1944-08">August</date> and I worked there until <date when="1944-11">November</date>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">work</term> was very hard, but the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food supply</term> was better there and we did not
				have to line up for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-487" type="subject">roll call</term>. Later <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp C</term> was disbanded and so was the <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_camp_kitchens">kitchen</term>. Then I was assigned to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">labourers transport</term> in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp D</term>. One thousand of us went out regularly
				to a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">workplace</term> that was eight kilometres away
				to perform earthwork. It was very hard; we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
					>worked</term> from 7 am to 3 pm. We got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject"
					>food</term> only in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> in the
				evening. We suffered a lot from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject">weather</term>.
				We often had to march and to <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-818" type="subject">mud and rain</term> in our bad <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">shoes</term>. We passed the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-501" type="subject">crematorium</term> every day. In <date when="1944-12"
					>December</date> we saw it being demolished. Meanwhile I got injured at <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term>: a tram hit my leg and I was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject">lying ill</term> for two weeks. My leg still hurts.
				They set me off for <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen-Belsen</placeName> with
				a <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521">transport</term> on <date when="1945-01-01"
					>January 1.</date> I, the aforementioned <persName ref="#ehri_et_bleier_jolan">Jolán Bleier</persName>, was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-411" type="subject">selected</term> on <date when="1944-09-15">September
					15</date> and taken to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-508" type="camp">Weisswasser</placeName>
				with a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">labourer’s transport</term> of 300. We were
				travelling for two days; 55 of us were in a freight car. We got one third of a loaf of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-833" type="subject">bread</term> and some <foreign xml:lang="de"
					>Zulage</foreign> for provisions as well as clean <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836"
					type="subject">clothes</term> and better <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject"
					>shoes</term>. In <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-508" type="camp">Weisswasser</placeName> we
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">stayed</term> in rooms: 12 persons in each. We
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in an armament <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term>; we went out to <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">work</term> in groups. We <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">worked</term> very hard for 10 hours a day. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food supply</term> was scarce and therefore we ate
				even <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">potato peels</term> and other <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">vegetables</term> from the garbage. I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> there until <date when="1945-02-02"
					>February 2</date>, when we were set off on foot. After walking for two days, we were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">entrained</term>. Fifty of us were put into one car
				and taken to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2898847/horneburg.html">Horneburg</placeName> on a five-day journey. We were
				given half a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">loaf of bread</term> and some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Zulage</term> for provisions. Just like in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-508" type="camp">Weisswasser</placeName>, we were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">working</term> in an armament <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term> for five weeks. However, we had a much stricter
				commander, an <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">Unterscharführer</term>, who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat us</term> severely for the slightest offence.
				Even very young <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825">girls</term> were sometimes
				sentenced for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">25 strokes</term>. If we queued up for
				another helping of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> at lunch and he
				noticed that, he beat and kicked us. We tried to avoid him in order to avoid being badly wounded. I was assigned to a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> once again on <date when="1945-04-13"
					>April 13</date>. After two days of travel we arrived in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42"
					type="camp">Bergen-Belsen</placeName>. I met my <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822"
					>sister</term>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_bleier_berta">Berta Bleier</persName> there two days before <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573">liberation</term>. She was <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556">working</term> hard in the <term type="subject"
					ref="#ehri_et_camp_kitchens">kitchen</term> and shortly after we met, she fell <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">ill</term> with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>. The <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004291">English</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us on <date when="1945-04-15">April
					15</date>, but the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_camp_kitchens">kitchen</term> continued to operate afterwards. From there we
				went to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-42" type="camp">Bergen</placeName> and then to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2940213/celle.html">Zelle</placeName>. We stayed there for four weeks and after that we came to
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Budapest</placeName> via <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3068160/pilsen.html">Pilsen</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>. Our plans for the future: as soon as our <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819">family</term> is reunited, which we hope for, we would
				like <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-203" type="subject">to go to</term>
				<placeName ref="#ehri_et_palestine">Palestine</placeName>.</p>
		</body>
	</text>
</TEI>
